es in South Africa by province since the 1994 South African general election. National place names, such as towns, suburbs, and natural landforms, are decided by the South African Geographical Names Council (SAGNC), and provinces have their own geographical names committees. Among the South African public, there is broad agreement that locations which are named after British or Afrikaner military personnel who fought against Black South Africans or contain racial slurs should be renamed, but efforts since 2005 to replace inoffensive names, such as Lydenburg (which African National Congress politicians claimed are necessary to "address the legacy of colonialism and apartheid") have faced opposition on the grounds of excessive costs and perceived bias in favour of honouring ANC members. Although many name changes have taken place officially since the end of apartheid in 1994, many of the previous names are still common in use, and some name changes have been officially reverted.\n\nPage: Provinces of South Africa\nSummary: South Africa is administered under nine provinces. On the eve of the 1994 general election, South Africa\'s former homelands, known as Bantustans, were reintegrated into the country, and the four provinces were increased to nine. The borders of Natal and the Orange Free State were retained, while the Cape Province and Transvaal Province were divided into three provinces each, plus North West Province which straddles the border of and contains territory from both these two former provinces. The twelfth, thirteenth and sixteenth amendments to the Constitution of South Africa changed the borders of seven of the provinces.\n\n--- [Automatic Crawl of Top Result: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Province] ---\nTitle: Cape Province\n\nURL Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Province\n\nPublished Time: 2002-03-16T02:51:16Z\n\nMarkdown Content:\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\n\n| Province of the Cape of Good Hope _Provinsie Kaap die Goeie Hoop_([Afrikaans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afrikaans_language "Afrikaans language")) |\n| --- |\n| Province of South Africa |\n| 1910–1994 |\n| [![Image 1: Coat of arms of Cape province](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/30/Coat_of_arms_of_the_Cape_Colony_1876-1994.svg/120px-Coat_of_arms_of_the_Cape_Colony_1876-1994.svg.png)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Coat_of_arms_of_the_Cape_Colony_1876-1994.svg "Coat of arms of Cape province") Coat of arms |\n| [![Image 2](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b5/Locator_map_of_Cape_Province_as_of_1_March_1994.svg/250px-Locator_map_of_Cape_Province_as_of_1_March_1994.svg.png)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Locator_map_of_Cape_Province_as_of_1_March_1994.svg) The Cape Province as it was by 1994 |\n| Capital | Cape Town |\n| Population |  |\n|  |\n| •1991 | 6,125,335[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Province#cite_note-RSAdist-1) |\n|  |\n| [Legislature](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legislature "Legislature") | [Cape Provincial Council](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Provincial_Council "Cape Provincial Council") |\n| History |  |\n|  |\n| •Established | 31 May 1910 |\n| •Disestablished | 27 April 1994 |\n|  |\n|  |\n| **Preceded by****Succeeded by** ![Image 3](h... [truncated]', name='wikipedia', id='2ecb3f5b-f28b-438d-8586-0af95676f0c3', tool_call_id='call_ce8af5b4545d49cb8493fec4'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 52, 'prompt_tokens': 10590, 'total_tokens': 10642, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 52}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 10590}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-c648ac2e-881f-9fff-837c-c9fb111d15b8', 'finish_reason': 'tool_ca