e specified time period.', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, id='20a3188d-2f58-4d29-8f91-b905b9f71197'), HumanMessage(content='# Research Topic\n\nHistorical Town Cemetery Research Plan\n\n# Completed Research Steps\n\n## Completed Step 1: Identify the Province and Town\n\n<finding>\n# Problem Statement\n\nThis research task seeks to identify a specific tombstone inscription from a cemetery in a small South African town. The key clues are:\n- The town is approximately 56 miles from the capital of a province founded in 1910 but renamed in the 1990s\n- Between 1905-1912, an Admiral lived on a farm near this town\n- The cemetery has slate tombstones with typical arch tops\n- Less than 10 graves belonged to imperial soldiers, with only 3 fenced\n- An article provided the name and full tombstone inscription for one of the fenced graves\n\n# Research Findings\n\n## Province Identification\n\nThe research confirmed that the **Cape Province** (officially the Province of the Cape of Good Hope) was established on May 31, 1910, when the Union of South Africa was formed. This province had **Cape Town** as its capital. In 1994, following South Africa\'s first democratic elections, the Cape Province was divided into three new provinces: the **Eastern Cape**, **Northern Cape**, and **Western Cape** (with portions also going to the North West Province). This matches the clue about a province "initially founded in 1910 but renamed in the 1990s."\n\n## Boer War Context\n\nThe Second Boer War (1899-1902) was fought between the British Empire and the two Boer republics (the South African Republic/Transvaal and the Orange Free State). British imperial soldiers who died during this conflict were buried in various cemeteries throughout South Africa. Many of these cemeteries contain graves with distinctive features including slate tombstones.\n\n## Search Limitations\n\nDespite multiple search attempts using various tools (common_search, web_search, and wikipedia), the following critical information could not be located:\n\n1. **The specific town** approximately 56 miles from Cape Town that matches all the described criteria\n2. **The Admiral** who lived on a farm near this town between 1905-1912\n3. **The specific article** describing the cemetery with slate tombstones, imperial soldier graves, and fenced graves\n4. **The tombstone inscription** that was published in the article\n\nThe searches returned general information about South African provinces, the Boer War, and cemeteries, but did not yield the specific historical article or cemetery records containing the tombstone inscription requested.\n\n## Potential Research Directions Not Fully Explored\n\nBased on the clues gathered, further research would need to focus on:\n- Small towns approximately 56 miles (90 km) from Cape Town in the Western Cape region\n- British Admirals who retired to South African farms after the Boer War era\n- Heritage articles or historical society publications about Boer War cemeteries in the Western Cape\n- Genealogical records of imperial soldiers buried in South Africa with fenced graves\n\n# Conclusion\n\nUnfortunately, this research was unable to locate the specific tombstone inscription requested. While the provincial context was confirmed (Cape Province, founded 1910, reorganized 1994, with Cape Town as capital), the searches did not identify the specific town, the Admiral who lived there, or the article containing the cemetery description and tombstone inscription. \n\nThe key missing elements are:\n- The name of the small town approximately 56 miles from Cape Town\n- The identity of the Admiral who lived on a farm near the town between 1905-1912\n- The specific article describing the cemetery with slate tombstones and imperial soldier graves\n- **The full tombstone inscription** from one of the three fenced imperial soldier graves\n\nTo obtain this information, additional research would need to access specialized South African historical archives, Boer War cemetery records, or local heritage society publications that document these specific graves with their inscriptions.\n\n# References\n\n- [Cape Province - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Province)\n\n- [List of renamed places in South Africa - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_renamed_places_in_South_Africa)\n\n- [Provinces of South Africa - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provinces_of_South_Africa)\n\n- [Second Boer War - Co-Curate](https://co-curate.ncl.ac.uk/boer-war/)\n\n- [Afrikaners - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afrikaners)\n\n- [South Africa War Graves Project](http://www.southafricawargraves.org/)\n</finding>\n\n# Current Step\n\n## Title\n\nFind Cemetery Article with Imperial Soldiers\n\n## Description\n\nSearch for articles about cemeteries in small South African towns that contain imperial soldier graves from the Boer War era, specifically looking for descriptions of slate tombstones with arch tops, less than 10 imperial soldier graves, with only 3 fenced graves, and any published tombstone inscriptions.\n\n## Locale\n\nen-US\n\nIMPORTANT: Your response MUST be written entirely in the language specified in the \'Locale\' section above (which is en-US). This applies to all sections of your response, including headers, content, and conclusions.\n\nIMPORTANT: Review the \'Completed Research Steps\' above carefully. If the information required for the \'Current Step\' has already been gathered in previous steps, DO NOT perform new searches. Instead, synthesize the existing information to answer the current step immediately. Only use tools if you are missing specific critical details.', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, id='659718bf-e75b-42e4-ac84-3100515d487a'), HumanMessage(content='IMPORTANT: DO NOT include inline citations in the text. Instead, track all sources and include a References section at the end using link reference format. Include an empty line between each citation for better readability. Use this format for each reference:\n- [Source Title](URL)\n\n- [Another Source](URL)', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, name='system', id='a5c587be-dfb5-4d7d-891f-e3ed1f822dd0'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 273, 'prompt_tokens': 16520, 'total_tokens': 16793, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 222, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 273}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 16520}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-580ed0ce-778e-9e83-bcbb-dd6d4ed62f38', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019ca321-e154-7eb1-bf95-8b0ecfc7aac3-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'web_search', 'args': {'__arg1': 'British Admiral retired South Africa farm after Boer War 1905 1910'}, 'id': 'call_96b3f27162654220baa91e8b', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 16520, 'output_tokens': 273, 'total_tokens': 16793, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 222}}), ToolMessage(content='Title: South African Wars (1879–1915) - Wikipedia\nLink: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_African_Wars_(1879–1915)\nSnippet: She travelled to the South African war zone on behalf of the South African Women and Children Distress Fund. In her report, she exposed the mistreatment of the women and children in the Boer refugee camps.\n\nTitle: The British in Africa, to 1910\nLink: http://www.fsmitha.com/h2/ch02-2.htm\nSnippet: He removed Boer women and children from their farms , and he began systematic drives against one small section of Boer country at a time. Deaths from poor sanitation and disease in the concentration camps killed around 20,000, and indignation arose around the globe.\n\nTitle: The South African War, 1899-1902 (or Second Boer War) – an ... Search Boer War military records online | Find by name ... Anglo-Boer War: how a bloody conflict 125 years ago still ... Boer War - National Army Museum The Boer War: British Imperialism in South Africa - Moments Log\nLink: https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/help-with-your-research/research-guides/the-south-african-war-1899-1902-overview/\nSnippet: Read our guides to British army soldiers and officers up to 1913for information on finding records of regular army officers and men who fought in South Africa . For guidance on finding records of the Imperial Yeomanry and African forces see our guides to Second Boer War personnel records and to Soldiers in African forces under British control. See full list on nationalarchives.gov.uk Although no naval engagements were fought at sea, detachments of Royal Marines and Royal Navy ratings and officers fought on land alongside soldiers. Medal rolls for the Queen’s and King’s South Africa medals can be downloaded from Discovery at ADM 171/53 and ADM 171/54 or searched by name on Ancestry (charges apply). The rolls also include the Sea... See full list on nationalarchives.gov.uk For guidance on finding records of men serving in the Royal Marines read our guide to Royal Marines other ranks. For officers’ records refer to Royal Marines officers. See full list on nationalarchives.gov.uk Our guide to Prisoners of war in British handshas a section on the Boer War . Lists of prisoners transported overseas can be found in the Admiralty, Transport Department series MT 23, along with other correspondence relating to prisoners and their transport. See full list on nationalarchives.gov.uk The Anglo- Boer War (1899-1902) saw tens of thousands of men from Britain , its Empire and the Commonwealth fight against the two Boer republics of South Africa . Here\'s how to uncover your family\'s connection to this major conflict using digitised military records. Oct 9, 2024 · The establishment of the Union of South Africa in 1910 brought the Boer and British colonies together under British authority. But it did not satisfy the expectations of Afrikaner... Field Marshal Frederick Sleigh Roberts was one of Britain’s most successful military commanders of the 19th century, winning victories during the Second Afghan War and revitalising the British campaign in the Boer War . Apr 29, 2025 · This treaty marked the end of the Boer Republics as independent entities, incorporating them into the British Empire and paving the way for the formation of the Union of South Africa in 1910 .\n\n--- [Automatic Crawl of Top Result: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_African_Wars_(1879–1915] ---\nTitle: South African Wars (1879–1915 - Wikipedia\n\nURL Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_African_Wars_(1879%E2%80%931915\n\nWarning: Target URL returned error 404: Not Found\n\nMarkdown Content:\nPage contents not supported in other languages.\n\n*   [Article](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=South_African_Wars_(1879%E2%80%931915&action=edit&redlink=1 "View the content page (page does not exist) [alt-c]")\n*   [Talk](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Talk:South_African_Wars_(1879%E2%80%931915&action=edit&redlink=1 "Discuss improvements to the content page (page does not exist) [alt-t]")\n\nTools\n\nActions\n\nGeneral\n\n*   [What links here](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:WhatLinksHere/South_African_Wars_(1879%E2%80%931915 "List of all English Wikipedia pages containing links to this page [alt-j]")\n*   [Upload file](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:File_Upload_Wizard "Upload files [alt-u]")\n*   Printable version\n*   [Page information](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=South_African_Wars_(1879%E2%80%931915&action=info "More information about this page")\n*   [Get shortened URL](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:UrlShortener&url=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FSouth_African_Wars_%281879%25E2%2580%259319