ific tombstone inscription from a cemetery in a small South African town. The key clues are:\n- The town is approximately 56 miles from the capital of a province founded in 1910 but renamed in the 1990s\n- Between 1905-1912, an Admiral lived on a farm near this town\n- The cemetery has slate tombstones with typical arch tops\n- Less than 10 graves belonged to imperial soldiers, with only 3 fenced\n- An article provided the name and full tombstone inscription for one of the fenced graves\n\n# Research Findings\n\n## Province Identification\n\nThe research identified **Natal Province** as a strong candidate for the province in question. Natal was one of the four provinces that formed the Union of South Africa on May 31, 1910. In 1994, following South Africa's first democratic elections, Natal Province was merged with the Zulu bantustan of KwaZulu to form **KwaZulu-Natal**. The capital of Natal Province was **Pietermaritzburg**, which remains the capital of KwaZulu-Natal today.\n\n## Town Identification Challenges\n\nThe research attempted to identify a town approximately 56 miles from Pietermaritzburg. **Camperdown** was discovered as a settlement in the Umgungundlovu District Municipality of KwaZulu-Natal. Interestingly, Camperdown was named to commemorate the victory of the British navy under **Admiral Adam Duncan** over the Dutch fleet at the Battle of Camperdown in October 1797. However, Camperdown is only approximately 20 km (12 miles) from Pietermaritzburg, not 56 miles, so it does not match the distance criterion.\n\n## Cemetery Research\n\nThe search located information about **Bultfontein Cemetery** in the Free State Province (formerly Orange Free State), which contains six tombstones of deceased Imperial soldiers from the Second Anglo-Boer War. However, this cemetery is not in KwaZulu-Natal and does not match all the specific criteria mentioned in the problem (slate tombstones with arch tops, exactly 3 fenced graves out of less than 10 imperial soldiers).\n\n## Admiral Connection\n\nWhile Admiral Adam Duncan's name is connected to the town of Camperdown through its naming, there is no evidence that an Admiral actually lived on a farm near Camperdown between 1905-1912. The research did not identify any British Admiral who retired to a farm near a town approximately 56 miles from Pietermaritzburg during this time period.\n\n## Missing Critical Information\n\nDespite extensive searching, the following critical information could not be located:\n\n1. **The specific town** approximately 56 miles from Pietermaritzburg that matches all criteria\n2. **The Admiral** who lived on a farm near this town between 1905-1912\n3. **The specific article** describing the cemetery with slate tombstones with arch tops, less than 10 imperial soldier graves, with exactly 3 fenced graves\n4. **The name of the soldier** whose grave was fenced\n5. **The full tombstone inscription** as provided in the article\n\n## Search Limitations\n\nThe search results included several LinkedIn job postings that appeared to match the exact phrasing of the user's question, suggesting this may be a specialized historical puzzle, quiz question, or genealogical research query that requires access to:\n- Local heritage society archives in KwaZulu-Natal\n- Specific historical articles about Boer War cemeteries in the region\n- Genealogical records of British naval officers who retired to South Africa\n- Specialized publications documenting imperial soldier graves with detailed inscriptions\n\n# Conclusion\n\nUnfortunately, this research was unable to locate the specific tombstone inscription requested. While the provincial context was confirmed (Natal Province, founded 1910, renamed KwaZulu-Natal in 1994, with Pietermaritzburg as capital), the searches did not successfully identify:\n\n- The specific small town approximately 56 miles from Pietermaritzburg\n- The Admiral who lived on a farm near the town between 1905-1912\n- The article describing the cemetery with slate tombstones and the specific grave details\n- **The full tombstone inscription** from one of the three fenced imperial soldier graves\n\nThe key finding that may provide a lead for future research is the connection between Admiral Adam Duncan and the town of Camperdown, though the distance from Pietermaritzburg does not match the 56-mile criterion. Further research would need to access specialized South African historical archives, local heritage society publications, or genealogical databases that document Boer War cemeteries in KwaZulu-Natal with detailed tombstone inscriptions.\n\n# References\n\n- [Cape Province - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Province)\n\n- [KwaZulu-Natal - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KwaZulu-Natal)\n\n- [Colony of Natal - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colony_of_Natal)\n\n- [Camperdown, South Africa - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camperdown,_South_Africa)\n\n- [List of heritage sites in KwaZulu-Natal - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_heritage_sites_in_KwaZulu-Natal)\n\n- [Visiting the Historic Bultfontein Cemetery - The Heritage Portal](https://www.theheritageportal.co.za/article/visiting-historic-bultfontein-cemetery)\n\n- [South African Wars (1879–1915) - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_African_Wars_(1879%E2%80%931915)\n\n- [The National Archives - South African War Research Guides](https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/help-with-your-research/research-guides/the-south-african-war-1899-1902-overview/)\n\n- [South Africa War Graves Project](http://www.southafricawargraves.org/)", additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, name='researcher', id='002a573d-08f1-4cfe-97b0-ac94aafe8bde', tool_calls=[], invalid_tool_calls=[]), HumanMessage(content='# Research Topic\n\nHistorical Town Cemetery Research Plan\n\n# Completed Research Steps\n\n## Completed Step 1: Identify the Province and Town\n\n<finding>\n# Problem Statement\n\nThis research task seeks to identify a specific tombstone inscription from a cemetery in a small South African town. The key clues are:\n- The town is approximately 56 miles from the capital of a province founded in 1910 but renamed in the 1990s\n- Between 1905-1912, an Admiral lived on a farm near this town\n- The cemetery has slate tombstones with typical arch tops\n- Less than 10 graves belonged to imperial soldiers, with only 3 fenced\n- An article provided the name and full tombstone inscription for one of the fenced graves\n\n# Research Findings\n\n## Province Identification\n\nThe research confirmed that the **Cape Province** (officially the Province of the Cape of Good Hope) was established on May 31, 1910, when the Union of South Africa was formed. This province had **Cape Town** as its capital. In 1994, following South Africa\'s first democratic elections, the Cape Province was divided into three new provinces: the **Eastern Cape**, **Northern Cape**, and **Western Cape** (with portions also going to the North West Province). This matches the clue about a province "initially founded in 1910 but renamed in the 1990s."\n\n## Boer War Context\n\nThe Second Boer War (1899-1902) was fought between the British Empire and the two Boer republics (the South African Republic/Transvaal and the Orange Free State). British imperial soldiers who died during this conflict were buried in various cemeteries throughout South Africa. Many of these cemeteries contain graves with distinctive features including slate tombstones.\n\n## Search Limitations\n\nDespite multiple search attempts using various tools (common_search, web_search, and wikipedia), the following critical information could not be located:\n\n1. **The specific town** approximately 56 miles from Cape Town that matches all the described criteria\n2. **The Admiral** who lived on a farm near this town between 1905-1912\n3. **The specific article** describing the cemetery with slate tombstones, imperial soldier graves, and fenced graves\n4. **The tombstone inscription** that was published in the article\n\nThe searches returned general information about South African provinces, the Boer War, and cemeteries, but did not yield the specific historical article or cemetery records containing the tombstone inscription requested.\n\n## Potential Research Directions Not Fully Explored\n\nBased on the clues gathered, further research would need to focus on:\n- Small towns approximately 56 miles (90 km) from Cape Town in the Western Cape region\n- British Admirals who retired to South African farms after the Boer War era\n- Heritage articles or historical society publications about Boer War cemeteries in the Western Cape\n- Genealogical records of imperial soldiers buried in South Africa with fenced graves\n\n# Conclusion\n\nUnfortunately, this research was unable to locate the specific tombstone inscription requested. While the provincial context was confirmed (Cape Province, founded 1910, reorganized 1994, with Cape Town as capital), the searches did not identify the specific town, the Admiral who lived there, or the article containing the cemetery description and tombstone inscription. \n\nThe key missing elements are:\n- The name of the small town approximately 56 miles from Cape Town\n- The identity of the Admiral who lived on a farm near the town between 1905-1912\n- The specific article describing the cemetery with slate tombstones and imperial soldier graves\n- **The full tombstone inscription** from one of the three fenced imperial soldier graves\n\nTo obtain this information, additional research would need to access specialized South African historical archives, Boer War cemetery records, or local heritage society publications that document these specific graves with their inscriptions.\n\n# References\n\n- [Cape Province - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Province)\n\n- [List of renamed places in South Africa - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_renamed_places_in_South_Africa)\n\n- [Provinces of South Africa - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provinces_of_South_Africa)\n\n- [Second Boer War - Co-Curate](https://co-curate.ncl.ac.uk/boer-war/)\n\n- [Afrikaners - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afrikaners)\n\n- [South Africa War Graves Project](http://www.southafricawargraves.org/)\n</finding>\n\n## Completed Step 2: Find Cemetery Article with Imperial Soldiers\n\n<finding>\n# Problem Statement\n\nThis research task seeks to identify a specific tombstone inscription from a cemetery in a small South African town. The key clues are:\n- The town is approximately 56 miles from the capital of a province founded in 1910 but renamed in the 1990s\n- Between 1905-1912, an Admiral lived on a farm near this town\n- The cemetery has slate tombstones with typical arch tops\n- Less than 10 graves belonged to imperial soldiers, with only 3 fenced\n- An article provided the name and full tombstone inscription for one of the fenced graves\n\n# Research Findings\n\n## Province Identification\n\nThe research identified **Natal Province** as a strong candidate for the province in question. Natal was one of the four provinces that formed the Union of South Africa on May 31, 1910. In 1994, following South Africa\'s first democratic elections, Natal Province was merged with the Zulu bantustan of KwaZulu to form **KwaZulu-Natal**. The capital of Natal Province was **Pietermaritzburg**, which remains the capital of KwaZulu-Natal today.\n\n## Town Identification Challenges\n\nThe research attempted to identify a town approximately 56 miles from Pietermaritzburg. **Camperdown** was discovered as a settlement in the Umgungundlovu District Municipality of KwaZulu-Natal. Interestingly, Camperdown was named to commemorate the victory of the British navy under **Admiral Adam Duncan** over the Dutch fleet at the Battle of Camperdown in October 1797. However, Camperdown is only approximately 20 km (12 miles) from Pietermaritzburg, not 56 miles, so it does not match the distance criterion.\n\n## Cemetery Research\n\nThe search located information about **Bultfontein Cemetery** in the Free State Province (formerly Orange Free State), which contains six tombstones of deceased Imperial soldiers from the Second Anglo-Boer War. However, this cemetery is not in KwaZulu-Natal and does not match all the specific criteria mentioned in the problem (slate tombstones with arch tops, exactly 3 fenced graves out of less than 10 imperial soldiers).\n\n## Admiral Connection\n\nWhile Admiral Adam Duncan\'s name is connected to the town of Camperdown through its naming, there is no evidence that an Admiral actually lived on a farm near Camperdown between 1905-1912. The research did not identify any British Admiral who retired to a farm near a town approximately 56 miles from Pietermaritzburg during this time period.\n\n## Missing Critical Information\n\nDespite extensive searching, the following critical information could not be located:\n\n1. **The specific town** approximately 56 miles from Pietermaritzburg that matches all criteria\n2. **The Admiral** who lived on a farm near this town between 1905-1912\n3. **The specific article** describing the cemetery with slate tombstones with arch tops, less than 10 imperial soldier graves, with exactly 3 fenced graves\n4. **The name of the soldier** whose grave was fenced\n5. **The full tombstone inscription** as provided in the article\n\n## Search Limitations\n\nThe search results included several LinkedIn job postings that appeared to match the exact phrasing of the user\'s question, suggesting this may be a specialized historical puzzle, quiz question, or genealogical research query that requires access to:\n- Local heritage society archives in KwaZulu-Natal\n- Specific historical articles about Boer War cemeteries in the region\n- Genealogical records of British naval officers who retired to South Africa\n- Specialized publications documenting imperial soldier graves with detailed inscriptions\n\n# Conclusion\n\nUnfortunately, this research was unable to locate the specific tombstone inscription requested. While the provincial context was confirmed (Natal Province, founded 1910, renamed KwaZulu-Natal in 1994, with Pietermaritzburg as capital), the searches did not successfully identify:\n\n- The specific small town approximately 56 miles from Pietermaritzburg\n- The Admiral who lived on a farm near the town between 1905-1912\n- The article describing the cemetery with slate tombstones and the specific grave details\n- **The full tombstone inscription** from one of the three fenced imperial soldier graves\n\nThe key finding that may provide a lead for future research is the connection between Admiral Adam Duncan and the town of Camperdown, though the distance from Pietermaritzburg does not match the 56-mile criterion. Further research would need to access specialized South African historical archives, local heritage society publications, or genealogical databases that document Boer War cemeteries in KwaZulu-Natal with detailed tombstone inscriptions.\n\n# References\n\n- [Cape Province - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Province)\n\n- [KwaZulu-Natal - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KwaZulu-Natal)\n\n- [Colony of Natal - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colony_of_Natal)\n\n- [Camperdown, South Africa - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camperdown,_South_Africa)\n\n- [List of heritage sites in KwaZulu-Natal - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_heritage_sites_in_KwaZulu-Natal)\n\n- [Visiting the Historic Bultfontein Cemetery - The Heritage Portal](https://www.theheritageportal.co.za/article/visiting-historic-bultfontein-cemetery)\n\n- [South African Wars (1879–1915) - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_African_Wars_(1879%E2%80%931915)\n\n- [The National Archives - South African War Research Guides](https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/help-with-your-research/research-guides/the-south-african-war-1899-1902-overview/)\n\n- [South Africa War Graves Project](http://www.southafricawargraves.org/)\n</finding>\n\n# Current Step\n\n## Title\n\nLocate Specific Tombstone Inscription\n\n## Description\n\nSearch for the specific article that provides the name and full tombstone inscription of one of the fenced imperial soldier graves. Look for historical records, heritage articles, or genealogical resources that document this cemetery and its Boer War graves with inscriptions.\n\n## Locale\n\nen-US\n\nIMPORTANT: Your response MUST be written entirely in the language specified in the \'Locale\' section above (which is en-US). This applies to all sections of your response, including headers, content, and conclusions.\n\nIMPORTANT: Review the \'Completed Research Steps\' above carefully. If the information required for the \'Current Step\' has already been gathered in previous steps, DO NOT perform new searches. Instead, synthesize the existing information to answer the current step immediately. Only use tools if you are missing specific critical details.', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}), HumanMessage(content='IMPORTANT: DO NOT include inline citations in the text. Instead, track all sources and include a References section at the end using link reference format. Include an empty line between each citation for better readability. Use this format for each reference:\n- [Source Title](URL)\n\n- [Another Source](URL)', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, name='system')]}
